.TH LXCMGR "1" "December 2025" "lxcmgr 202208211259-git" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lxcmgr \- LXD/LXC container management utility (also known as lxdmgr)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lxcmgr
[\fI\,OPTIONS\/\fR] [\fI\,COMMAND\/\fR] [\fI\,NAME\/\fR] [\fI\,IMAGE\/\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lxcmgr
(also accessible as
.BR lxdmgr )
is a simplified management interface for LXD/LXC system containers. It provides an easy-to-use command-line interface for common container operations including creation, lifecycle management, and web panel setup.
.PP
LXD is a next generation system container and virtual machine manager built on top of LXC (Linux Containers). lxcmgr simplifies the management of LXD containers by providing convenient wrapper commands for the most common operations, making container management more accessible without requiring deep knowledge of LXD's full command set.
.PP
The tool supports container lifecycle management (start, stop, restart, delete), container interaction (exec commands), image management, status checking, and includes web panel integration for graphical management.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B init
Initialize and setup LXD/LXC on the system. This command configures LXD with default settings, sets up storage pools, network bridges, and prepares the system for container operations.
.TP
.B info
Display LXD system information including version, storage backends, network configuration, and resource usage.
.TP
.B panel
Setup and configure the LXD web interface panel for graphical container management through a browser.
.TP
.B images
List available container images from configured remotes (Ubuntu, Alpine, Debian, etc.).
.TP
.B list
List all containers on the system showing their names, status, IP addresses, and image information.
.TP
.B check \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Check the status of a specific container including its state (running/stopped), resource usage, and configuration.
.TP
.B search \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Search for available container images matching the specified name across all configured image remotes.
.TP
.B create \fI\,<name> <image>\/\fR
Create a new container with the specified name using the specified image. Common images include ubuntu:22.04, alpine:latest, debian:bookworm.
.TP
.B start \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Start a stopped container. The container will boot and become available for use.
.TP
.B stop \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Stop a running container gracefully. The container will be shut down cleanly.
.TP
.B restart \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Restart a container by stopping and starting it. This is useful for applying configuration changes.
.TP
.B delete \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Delete a container and its associated data. This action cannot be undone.
.TP
.B exec \fI\,<name> <command>\/\fR
Execute a command inside a running container. This is similar to "docker exec" or SSH access.
.TP
.B run \fI\,<name>\/\fR
Run a container operation (implementation specific to container configuration).
